>>It's a legacy role with a much too wide set of permissions, and should be avoided if at all possible.
>
>That may be, but lots of people are using it, now. We need to try to avoid or at least minimize how badly we break these people.

If we're breaking people why not break them in a way that encourages best practices? I suppose we could do something like:

```
# in iam.Policy
@property
def legacy_owners(self):
   return self.bindings.setdefault('roles/owner', set())

@legacy_owners.setter
def legacy_owners(self, values):
   assert isinstance(values, set)
   self.bindings['roles/owner'] = values

@property
def owners(self):
   return frozenset(self.legacy_owners | self.bindings.get(self._ADMIN_ROLE, set()))

@owners.setter
def owners(self, values):
  raise ValuesError("Nope")

# in pubsub.iam.Policy

_ADMIN_ROLE = 'roles/pubsub.admin'

@property
def admins(self):
  return self.bindings.set_default(self._ADMIN_ROLE, set())
```

Since I mentioned functional vs imperative programming before:

Within a `filter` method (and `map` also), it's helpful to conceptualize the inner function's main purpose as operating on a single item. It can be good to avoid thinking about 'iteration' with these.

The result is that parts of the logic can be cleanly decomposed. For example, something like:

```javascript
methods: {
  userComparator(user1, user2) {
    if (user1.username[0] > user2.username[0]) { return 1; }
    else if (user1.username[0] < user2.username[0]) { return -1; }
    return 0;
  },
  matchesTextFilter(user) {
    const full_name = user.full_name.toLowerCase();
    const username = user.username.toLowerCase();
    const terms = this.searchFilter.split(' ').filter(Boolean).map(val => val.toLowerCase());
    return terms.every(term => full_name.includes(term) || username.includes(term));
  },
  matchesRoleFilter(user) {
    if (this.roleFilter === 'all') {
      return true;
    }
    return user.kind === this.roleFilter;
  },
}
computed: {
  visibleUsers() {
    return this.users
      .filter(user => this.matchesTextFilter(user) && this.matchesRoleFilter(user))
      .sort(this.userComparator);
  },
},
```

